# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1873-philadelphia-white-stockings-season] The **Philadelphia White Stockings** played their first season in 1873 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1873-philadelphia-white-stockings-season] They finished second in the league with a record of 36–17.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-baltimore-canaries-season] The **Baltimore Canaries** played their final season in 1874 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-baltimore-canaries-season] They finished eighth in the league with a record of 9–38.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] The **1874 Boston Red Stockings season** was the fourth season of the franchise.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] They won their third consecutive National Association championship.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Managed by Harry Wright, Boston finished with a record of 52–18 to win the pennant by 7.5 games.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Pitcher Al Spalding started 69 of the Red Stockings' games and led the NA with 52 wins.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Outfielder Cal McVey led the league with 71 runs batted in, and he paced the Boston offense which scored more runs than any other team.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-boston-red-stockings-season] Harry Wright, Al Spalding, first baseman Jim O'Rourke, catcher Deacon White, and shortstop George Wright have all been elected into the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-brooklyn-atlantics-season] The **Brooklyn Atlantics** played in 1874 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-brooklyn-atlantics-season] They finished sixth in the league with a record of 22–33.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-hartford-dark-blues-season] The Hartford Dark Blues were formed by Morgan Bulkeley and joined the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players for the 1874 season.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-hartford-dark-blues-season] They finished in seventh place in their debut.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season] The **Philadelphia White Stockings** played in 1874 as a member of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players.
[src:1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season/1874-philadelphia-white-stockings-season] They finished fourth in the league with a record of 29–29.
